2026-04-16 12:14:00 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['PSU internal wiring / PCB between battery terminals and the rest of the circuit'] hypothesis_explanation='A new, known-good 12 V battery has been installed. Continuity tests (with battery removed) show low-ohm paths from the battery terminals to both PSU output cables and to the LED+resistor branch, yet with the battery inserted the measured voltage at the output cables and across the LED branch is essentially 0 V. The PSU LED is also off. The fact that the voltage remains 0 V even with all downstream modules disconnected proves there is no external short or overload. This combination—good battery, verified low-resistance paths when unpowered, but 0 V everywhere when powered—indicates that the battery terminals are not actually delivering their voltage into the circuit when the battery is installed. The most plausible root cause is a defect local to the power-supply module’s internal interconnect between the physical battery contacts and the rest of the wiring/PCB (e.g., misaligned or damaged battery contacts, a cracked trace or cold joint right at the terminals, or reversed/isolated battery holder connections). Under ohmmeter conditions the meter’s probes bypass that defect, so continuity appears good, but under real operation the circuit is effectively open, leaving the whole chain unpowered. Therefore the remaining fault lies in the PSU internal wiring/PCB at or immediately adjacent to the battery terminals, preventing the 12 V from reaching the LED branch and output cables.'
